# Color Palette Usage

Always use the project's custom color palette defined in Tailwind configuration.

## Where Colors Are Defined

Colors can be defined in two places with Tailwind 4:

1. **CSS-first in `resources/css/app.css`:**

```css
@theme {
    --color-primary: #3b82f6;
    --color-secondary: #10b981;
    --color-accent: #f59e0b;
    --color-danger: #ef4444;
}
```

2. **JavaScript config in `tailwind.config.js`** (for complex configurations)

## Using Custom Colors

```blade
{{-- ✅ GOOD - Use custom palette colors --}}
<button class="bg-primary text-white hover:bg-primary-dark">
    Submit
</button>

<div class="text-secondary border-secondary">
    Success message
</div>

{{-- ❌ BAD - Avoid arbitrary color values --}}
<button class="bg-[#3b82f6]">Submit</button>
<div class="text-[rgb(16,185,129)]">Text</div>
```

## Consistency

- Use the defined color palette across all components
- Maintain consistent color usage for similar UI elements
- Document color usage in design system if needed
- Add new colors to the configuration file, not inline
- Use semantic color names (primary, secondary, success, danger, warning, info)

## Checking Current Palette

```bash
# View current Tailwind configuration
cat resources/css/app.css | grep "@theme" -A 20
cat tailwind.config.js
```

Always check the project's color configuration before adding new colors or components.
